English personal name <i>James</i>. Introduced to England by the Normans, this is an Old French form of Late Latin <i>Iacomus</i>, a variant of Latin <i>Iacobus</i>, Greek <i>Iakōbos</i>, the New Testament rendering of Hebrew <i>Ya‘aqob</i> (see   Jacob  ). The medieval Latin (Vulgate) Bible distinguished between Old Testament <i>Iacob</i> (which was uninflected) and New Testament <i>Iacobus</i> (with inflections). The latter developed into <i>James</i> in medieval French. The distinction was carried over into the King James Bible of 1611, and   Jacob   and <i>James</i> remain as separate names in English usage. Most European languages, however, make no such distinction, so that forms such as French   Jacques  , stand for both the Old and the New Testament names. This surname is also very common among African Americans. Compare   Jack  ."]}]},{"name":"Elspet","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Scottish: Scottish forms of Elizabeth."],"variants":[{"name":"Elspeth","meanings":["contracted form of   Elizabeth  , also found outside Scotland."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Elspet Elizabeth Jamie was born in 1590, in Gargunnock, Stirlingshire, Scotland, her father, Peter Jane, was 24 and her mother, Lady Elizabeth Jamie Combes, was 19. She had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Patrick Gilchrist. She died on 15 March 1623, in her hometown, at the age of 33."},"et":{"1590–15 March 1623":"1590–15. märts 1623","1590–1623":"1590–1623","1587–1616":"1587–1616","1613–1714":"1613–1714","1615–1652":"1615–1652","1615–Male":"1615–Surnud","1566–1640":"1566–1640","1571–1642":"1571–1642","15 March 1623":"15. märts 1623","1571":"1571","1590":"1590","1613":"1613","23 March 1616":"23. märts 1616","1623":"1623","1566":"1566","25 July 1615":"25. juuli 1615","1642":"1642","1587":"1587","1652":"1652","1640":"1640","1616":"1616","1615":"1615","1714":"1714","7 July 1615":"7. juuli 1615","Gargunnock, Stirling, Scotland":"Gargunnock, Stirlingshire, Scotland","Gargunnock, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Gargunnock, Stirlingshire, Scotland","Dunbar, East Lothian, Scotland":"Dunbar, Haddingtonshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1590–15 March 1623":"1590–15. maaliskuuta 1623","1590–1623":"1590–1623","1587–1616":"1587–1616","1613–1714":"1613–1714","1615–1652":"1615–1652","1615–Male":"1615–Kuollut","1566–1640":"1566–1640","1571–1642":"1571–1642","15 March 1623":"15. maaliskuuta 1623","1571":"1571","1590":"1590","1613":"1613","23 March 1616":"23. maaliskuuta 1616","1623":"1623","1566":"1566","25 July 1615":"25. heinäkuuta 1615","1642":"1642","1587":"1587","1652":"1652","1640":"1640","1616":"1616","1615":"1615","1714":"1714","7 July 1615":"7. heinäkuuta 1615","Gargunnock, Stirling, Scotland":"Gargunnock, Stirlingshire, Scotland","Gargunnock, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Gargunnock, Stirlingshire, Sc